g.title: j1040825559
g.text: Dear? If you're there, I could use your ear.

g.title: j183536959->j1040825559
g.text: true

g.title: j3486387978
g.text: If you’re there, I could use a friend.

g.title: j183536959->j3486387978
g.text: false

g.title: j2102986809
g.text: Check boolean EleanorArthurNightmare

g.title: j1620454874
g.text: I’m having the Arthur dreams again. The ones where he has to kill me.

g.title: j2102986809->j1620454874
g.text: true

g.title: j1645717299
g.text: I keep having this terrible dream about Arthur where he has to kill me. And as he shoves the blade between my ribs I’m screaming “Eleanor is RIGHT HERE, you stupid bastard!” but he can’t hear me any more.

g.title: j2102986809->j1645717299
g.text: false

g.title: j2968175293
g.text: I’m here. It’s okay.

g.title: j5866127
g.text: [Ignore.]

g.title: j3982651481
g.text: Boolean EleanorArthurNightmare is now true.

g.title: j3303909935
g.text: Arthur’s not going to kill you, Eleanor. You’re his sister. He knows that.

g.title: Chat ends.
g.text: Chat ends.

g.title: j3951108063
g.text: That’s just it, though. ‘You’re not my sister any more.’ That’s what he says in the dream. Then he stabs me through the chest with his toy sword.

g.title: j4030226301
g.text: We’re only little kids in the dream, if it wasn’t already messed up enough.

g.title: j2321057562
g.text: It’s not real. I don’t believe Arthur would ever hurt you, no matter how Infested you were.

g.title: j1625055719
g.text: ... Yikes.

g.title: j1192486217
g.text: Not even to ‘put me out of my misery’? Not even if I was suffering?

g.title: j3287494727
g.text: Yeah. That's the worst part.

g.title: j233586014
g.text: He’s his father’s son. He’s all about doing the right thing, not the easy thing.

g.title: j2118294304
g.text: It's so vivid, so real. Like I'm remembering something that actually happened.

g.title: j3448373454
g.text: However bad you think your family was, it's nothing compared to some I've met.

g.title: j2053248598
g.text: Wait. What’s your father got to do with this?

g.title: j2726160525
g.text: I'm sure Arthur wouldn't actually do that, though.

g.title: j785145478
g.text: Maybe you should talk to Arthur about it?

g.title: j1759009227
g.text: I'm sure. The future is quite inventive in its cruelty.

g.title: j4225245970
g.text: Everything.

g.title: j100005312
g.text: I can't. He’s his father’s son. He’s all about doing the right thing, not the easy thing.

g.title: j878742068
g.text: But my concern here is with the past.

g.title: j3544908555
g.text: You’re going to have to give me more than that if you want me to understand.

g.title: j1227495667
g.text: Eleanor. Please stop being obtuse on purpose.

g.title: j519423675
g.text: It’s one of the many, many things we don’t talk about.

g.title: j440480879
g.text: I'm not.

g.title: j2270790668
g.text: We don’t talk about what happened in Cavona, we don’t talk about Christopher and we NEVER talk about Granny Callie.

g.title: j3167685548
g.text: I'm honestly trying my best to explain.

g.title: j3236349158
g.text: Then maybe you shouldn't.

g.title: j507207830
g.text: Then maybe you should.

g.title: j3901754327
g.text: My father set the example for the way Arthur and deal with issues between us. Or rather, the way we don't.

g.title: j1917161169
g.text: Maybe I shouldn't.

g.title: j3378307182
g.text: Maybe I should.

g.title: j3476362560
g.text: Maybe it’s time.

g.title: j1461714671
g.text: Do you want the whole story? Or shall I boil it down to essentials?

g.title: j302031602
g.text: I’m not going anywhere. Give me the whole thing.

g.title: j1597456301
g.text: Can I get the abridged version?

g.title: j2538044526
g.text: Granny Callie was our paternal grandmother. Callista Penrose Nightingale.

g.title: j2046102841
g.text: Granny Callie was desperately sick. Demented. Our father suffocated her to death with a pillow rather than let her go on suffering. I hope that's curt enough for you.

g.title: j3872611908
g.text: She had Pelham’s Syndrome. You’ve probably cured it by now (she said with an inward wrench). It chips away at a person’s mind. Instead of watching someone you live die all at once, they fade away slowly, by degrees, like an old photograph parching in the sunlight, or a video copied too many times over.

g.title: j1061493123
g.text: Like what was happening to Suda that made her decide to become a Cephalon. I understand.

g.title: j873728209
g.text: Actually... no, we haven't really cured that...

g.title: j738971180
g.text: When she first came to live with us, Arthur and I were so excited. To us, she was the lovely old woman who smelled of violets and told stories where she did all the different voices. She gave us actual folding money on our birthdays. We thought it would be like a birthday all the time.

g.title: j4202490090
g.text: Then she started to go downhill. At first she was just forgetful. Then she started confusing us with other people. She called me Albertine and Arthur, Charlie. Demanded to know where Jimmy had run off to. We never found out whether Jimmy was a dog or a cat or a boyfriend.

g.title: j106887926
g.text: Then she started talking to people who weren’t there. Then she started wandering the house after dark.

g.title: j4277643065
g.text: That must have been frightening for you both.

g.title: j748644805
g.text: Oh, Void.

g.title: j3053130765
g.text: I remember going for a wee in the middle of the night and seeing her lurching towards me down the corridor in the dark, groaning, her face all twisted up and her hair like a mad clown wig. I couldn’t stop screaming.

g.title: j2842261510
g.text: When it got really bad, she would lie in bed and shriek. We’d go out to school in the morning and when I turned down our lane, my heart would sink because I could hear her from ten houses away, still screaming, eight hours later.

g.title: j944992392
g.text: Our dad used to talk about putting a pillow over her face. We thought he was joking, because of course he was, that’s his mum.

g.title: j3895513344
g.text: And now a lot of things make sense.

g.title: j3798931184
g.text: One night she was screaming, and the screams just stopped. I got up and went to Arthur’s room. He was awake, of course. We sat together listening and listening, and then we heard the door to her room close.

g.title: j2644658105
g.text: Died in her sleep, Dad said the next day.

g.title: j3947112763
g.text: And you’re scared that Arthur might do the same to you?

g.title: j568578842
g.text: Arthur isn't your father. He wouldn't do what he did.

g.title: j2127641010
g.text: If he honestly thought it was for the best?

g.title: j1715146279
g.text: You have no way of knowing that. If Arthur honestly thought it was for the best?

g.title: j3903754617
g.text: I don’t know. Maybe. It seems a lot less likely now I’ve actually told someone.

g.title: j1449256695
g.text: +20 Chemistry

g.title: j4272043006
g.text: You’re wonderful. Thank you for bearing with me. I needed to get that out.

g.title: j3466080007
g.text: Boolean EleanorDreams is now true.
